#! /usr/bin/perl -w
use strict;

=head1 NAME

hplot - plot histogram of events

=head1 SYNOPSIS

hplot [options] file

=head1 DESCRIPTION

Plots a histogram of events binned against some column. By default all
events are binned versus time (see I<--bincol> to change this), with a bin
size of 1 (see I<--binsize> to change the binning size).

=head1 OPTIONS

=over 4

=item --help

Show help and exit.

=item --version

Show version and exit.

=item --bincol=s

Column to bin against. Default is I<time>.

=item --binsize=s

Size of each bin. Default is 1.

=item --line

Plot histogram values as a line plot.

=item --points

Plot histogram values as points.

=item --err

Draw error bars, calculated as square root of the number of events
in each bin.

=item --low=f --high=f

Central values for the first and last bins. Defaults are min/max of the
binned column.

=item --xlog --ylog

Use logarithmic scale for I<x> and I<y> axes.

=item --dev=s

PGPLOT output device. Defaults to contents of environment variable
I<PGPLOT_DEV> if it exists, otherwise I</xs>. Available devices can be
listed with the I<--dlist> option.

=item --dlist

List available PGPLOT devices and exit.

=item --extname=s

FITS binary table containing data. Default is I<events>.

=item --title=s --xtitle=s --ytitle=s

Title for plot, and I<x> and I<y> axes.

=item --dcolor=i --tcolor=i --acolor=i

Colors for data, text and axes, respectively. These are PGPLOT colors,
and must be specified by number. The PGPLOT colors are listed below.
Note that whether background and foreground colors are black or white
depends on the plotting device, and these can be swapped with the
I<--cinvert> option.

=over 4

0 = background color

1 = foreground color

2 = red

3 = green

4 = blue

5 = cyan

6 = magenta

7 = yellow

=back

=item --cinvert

Exchange foreground and background colors. Useful for plotting black
on white on some devices (e.g., PNG image).

=item --xoffset=f --xscale=f

Offset and scale I<x> values before binning. Note that offset is
performed before scaling.

=item --print

Print histogram data to stdout in the form of an rdb table.

=item --rfilter=s

Event filtering can be achieved using the --rfilter option. This option expects
a string in the cfitsio-style row filtering syntax. Some examples...

=over 4

To use only events whose PHA is less than 255:

    hplot --rfilter='pha < 255' evt.fits

=back

=over 4

To use only events in a bounding box in tdetx, tdety space, pha values
less than 255:

    hplot --rfilter='pha<255 && tdetx>10 && tdetx<20 && tdety>10 && tdety<20' evt.fits

=back

=over 4

To plot events versus pha in a circular region in x, y space centered about (10,20) with a
radius of 5, with low and high PHA values of 60 and 150:

    hplot --bincol=pha --rfilter='circle(10,20,5,x,y)' --low=60 --high=150 evt.fits

=back

CFITSIO has a numer of useful row-filtering capabilities, see
https://heasarc.gsfc.nasa.gov/docs/software/fitsio/c/c_user/node102.html
for more details.

=item --gti

Filter events on GTI.

=item --gtiext=s

Name of the GTI table. The default value is 'gti'.

=item --gtifile=s

File from which to read the GTI table. Default is the event file. Use of this
option implies I<--gti>

=item --gtiscale

Scale bins to compensate for GTI. Only valid if I<--bincol=time>. Use of this
option implies I<--gti>.

=back

=head1 AUTHOR

Pete Ratzlaff E<lt>pratzlaff@cfa.harvard.eduE<gt> May 2006

=head1 SEE ALSO

perl(1).

=cut

